"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody. Every so often I'll hear somebody, and by every so often I mean all the time, I hear people talk about giving their plants nutrients. And you gotta give your plants nutrients because they they feed off nutrients that helps them create the building blocks of of their structure and nutrients and nutrients and blah blah blah. I don't give my plants nutrients, uh, and I really don't believe in the concept. I think that there's a miss here where people think that biological entities, complex ones like ourselves and the plants and things like this, all absorb nutrients because they're directly given these nutrients, and they can, but this isn't a very good system. The plants and the nutrients have a gap between them. This gap is filled by the microbes. But microbes are actually what break down the polymers into monomers, nutrients, and then provide them to the plants exactly as the plants need them, exactly as the plants ask for them. There's communication between the plants and the microbes. The microbes deliver exactly what the plants need, and in return the plants return carbon to the soil, and that's what the microbes want. So there's this exchange going on, but the plants don't absorb nutrients directly, they're fed these nutrients by the microbes. And when we go around that process, when we provide the ammonia, for instance, directly to the plants to absorb, they can, but without any sort of regulation, without any sort of interaction, without any sort of exchange. This isn't healthy for the plants. This isn't the ideal way for them to go about their business of incorporating nutrients. And so I don't worry about nutrients because I know that giving the plants nutrients directly is not a good idea. I want to provide organic matter that microbes can break down and then feed the plants from that. There's a process of biological churning within the soil that's really what you're looking for. Not nutrients. You're looking for microbes. You're looking for a good biological churn where there's a lot of organic matter for those microbes to work from. And that's the way nature does it. It's a much better system than us providing nutrients. So don't think about nutrients. Think about microbes. Think about providing microbes with raw material to break down and give to your plants, but don't give them the raw material itself. They don't want it. They don't need it. It's not exactly how it's done. And it leads to all sorts of problems with the plant and its resilience to disease and pestilence. Because those nutrients that the that you're giving directly are not form-fitted the way the microbes are going to form fit those nutrients. Where they're going to get exactly what they need, exactly how they need it, exactly when they need it. And you can't do that by just giving them raw nutrients. So don't do it. Give them biology, give them microbes, give them organic matter, and watch your garden just flourish without any sort of over or under or any sort of deficiencies or any sort of uh pestilence problems or disease problems. Because when the microbes feed the plants, you get a health that you can't really define through normal conventional means. It explodes with health. It gives you health in ways that you wouldn't even imagine. Anyway, don't worry about your nutrients. Worry about your microbes. Or at least that's what I do. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody.\",\n      \"start\": 0.16,\n      \"end\": 1.12,\n      \"duration\": 0.96,\n      \"confidence\": 0.979,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.16,\n          \"end\": 0.32,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.989\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.32,\n          \"end\": 0.4,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever